<worksheet>
  <title>Homework 5</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Foundations of Mathematics</alert>
    </p>
  </introduction>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Prove that for every <m>n\in{\bf Z}^+</m>, <me>\sum_{i = 1}^n i(i+1) = 1\cdot 2 + 2\cdot 3 + \cdots + n(n+1)
		= \frac{n(n+1)(n+2)}3.</me>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Recall that the Fibonacci numbers are <m>F_1 = 1</m>, <m>F_2 = 1</m>, and <me>F_{n + 1} = F_n + F_{n-1}</me> for all <m>n\geq 2</m>.
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Prove that for every <m>n\in{\bf Z}^+</m>, <me>\sum_{j = 1}^n (F_j)^2 = F_n\cdot F_{n+1}.</me>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Consider the relation <m>\sim</m> on <m>{\bf R}</m> given by <me>x\sim y\Longleftrightarrow |x - y| &lt; 1.</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Is <m>\sim</m> reflexive? Is <m>\sim</m> symmetric? Is <m>\sim</m> transitive? Prove your answers.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Consider the relation <m>\approx</m> on <m>{\bf Z}^+\times{\bf Z}^+</m> defined by <me>(a,b)\approx(c,d)\Longleftrightarrow ad = bc.</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Prove that <m>\approx</m> is an equivalence relation.
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

	
